<title>Paper Scout Research Report — 2026-06-12</title>

<p>This run covered the 2026-06-11/12 paper pool and found three strong threads. The common pattern is a deliberate split between <b>memory that persists across time</b> and <b>computation that runs on demand</b>: LabVLA builds a simulation data engine to pre-train embodied memory for laboratory protocols; MoVerse offloads long-range scene memory into an explicit panoramic Gaussian scaffold so a causal video model only has to refine local observations; and SpatialClaw shows that the action interface itself—code executed in a persistent kernel—can be a larger win for spatial agents than adding more tools. Below each thread is backed by code inspection, small probes, and comparisons with neighbors.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
<p><b>Standout:</b> SpatialClaw is the clearest seed for a research thread. Its controlled ablation shows that replacing structured tool-calls with a persistent Python cell interface gains +11.2 pp on 20 spatial-reasoning benchmarks, with the largest lifts exactly where chained geometric computation across frames or viewpoints is required.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 1 — Embodied Intelligence in Structured Worlds</h1>

<p>Two papers tackle embodied or world-model settings where the scene itself is the hard part: a scientific laboratory for VLAs, and a single-image explorable world for real-time video roaming.</p>

