<h2>LabVLA: Grounding VLAs in Scientific Laboratories</h2>
<p>Ren et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.13578">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.13578">PDF</a> · <a href="https://zjunlp.github.io/LabVLA/">Project</a></p>

<p>The paper’s central claim is that scientific-lab manipulation is a <b>data-and-embodiment bottleneck</b>, not a policy-architecture bottleneck. Existing robot corpora (Open X-Embodiment, DROID, BridgeData) rarely contain pipettes, centrifuges, transparent liquids, or protocol-level workflows, so a VLA trained only on them cannot ground a written lab protocol in the right instruments and physical states. LabVLA’s response is two-fold: RoboGenesis, an Isaac Sim–based data engine that composes configured lab workflows from atomic skills across 16 robot embodiments, and LabVLA, a Qwen3-VL-4B policy trained with FAST action-token pretraining followed by flow-matching posttraining under knowledge insulation.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:labvla:framework]]</p>

<p>RoboGenesis is the more novel half. It generates assets (text → image → TRELLIS 2.0 mesh → USD with collision metadata), assembles validated lab scenes through a seeded greedy placement solver, decomposes natural-language protocols into ordered atomic skills, instantiates them across robot profiles, and exports only successful rollouts with 15 annotation streams. The paper compares synthetic-data engines in Table 1 and argues that only RoboGenesis combines generative asset creation, workflow composition, cross-embodiment deployment, domain randomization, and success-filtered structured export.</p>

<p>The policy half is deliberately conservative: Qwen3-VL-4B backbone + an 18-layer DiT action expert. The training recipe has two stages. In pretraining, continuous actions are tokenized with FAST and the VLM is trained to predict those discrete action tokens alongside VQA and language subtasks, so the visual-language prefix becomes action-aware before any continuous head is attached. In posttraining, a DiT action expert is attached and trained with flow matching to predict 50-step action chunks. A stop-gradient (<b>knowledge insulation</b>) blocks flow-matching gradients from reaching the VLM prefix while FAST and annotation cross-entropy losses remain active, preventing the action objective from corrupting language and visual grounding.</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="Flow-matching action chunk (simplified)"><code>x_t = tau * A_gt + (1 - tau) * noise
u_t = A_gt - noise
v_theta = dit(x_t, tau, state, proj(vlm_prefix))  # VLM prefix detached under KI
loss = MSE(v_theta, u_t) + lambda_fast * CE_FAST + lambda_ann * CE_ann</code></pre>

<p>We inspected the public code at <code>zjunlp/LabVLA</code> and found it matches the paper’s hyperparameters closely: VLM pretrain on Robointer-VQA + AgiBot World Beta + OXE-AugE + DROID, 3×8 A100s, 100k steps; KI posttrain on OXE-AugE + LabEmbodied-Data, 2×8 A100s, 80k steps, <code>ki_mse_weight=10.0</code>, 10 Euler inference steps. The DiT uses interleaved self-attention blocks (odd-indexed layers self-attend over state and action tokens) to let action tokens exchange temporal information, a detail the paper does not emphasize. A deliberate legacy choice in the code places the state soft token before the vision+language prefix rather than after, noted in comments as a checkpoint bit-compatibility issue.</p>

<p>The biggest unresolved question is availability. RoboGenesis and LabEmbodied-Data are described in detail but are <b>not in the public repository</b> as of this run; the README lists them as pending releases. Without them, the data-engine claim is hard to replicate externally. We therefore built a toy reconstruction (<code>runs/2026-06-12-spatialclaw-moverse-labvla/labvla-2606.13578/code/toy_robogenesis_workflow.py</code>) that captures the workflow-composition and domain-randomization semantics, plus FAST and flow-matching sketches in NumPy.</p>

<p>On LabUtopia, LabVLA leads baselines in average success (71.1% ID / 70.0% OOD), but the task breakdown is telling: <b>Pour Liquid</b> sits far below the others (43.3% ID / 34.2% OOD), confirming that liquid-state tracking and fine tilt control remain unsolved. The real-robot Franka study shows simulation pretraining transfers to four benchtop tasks, but the gap to real wet-lab deployment is large. LabVLA is best understood as a careful integration of a lab-protocol data engine with a π0.5-style policy recipe; the architecture itself is not the novelty, but the connection between data engine, cross-embodiment schema, and knowledge-insulated training is.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>MoVerse: Real-Time Video World Modeling with Panoramic Gaussian Scaffold</h2>
<p>Zhou et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.13376">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.13376">PDF</a> · <a href="https://orange-3dv-team.github.io/MoVerse/">Project</a></p>

<p>MoVerse asks: can a single narrow-field-of-view image become an interactively navigable, photorealistic world? The difficulty is that the input observes only a small frustum, while roaming requires a complete surrounding world, persistent geometry, controllable camera motion, and temporally coherent frames. MoVerse’s answer is to <b>separate world construction from observation rendering</b>. Stages I and II run once offline to build a panoramic Gaussian scaffold; Stage III streams video online through a causal autoregressive renderer conditioned on that scaffold.</p>

<p>Stage I expands the input into a gravity-aligned 360° ERP panorama. A differentiable auto-leveling module estimates a rigid spherical rotation that removes pitch and roll, avoiding the jelly-like warps of an unconstrained spatial transformer. Circular latent encoding and a shift-equivariance loss make the diffusion model respect the horizontal S¹ topology of ERP panoramas, rather than treating the left/right boundary as an artificial image edge.</p>

<p>Stage II lifts the panorama into a 3D Gaussian scaffold. Each ERP pixel maps to longitude <latex>\theta</latex> and latitude <latex>\phi</latex>, with viewing direction <latex>\mathbf{d}(\theta,\phi)</latex>. Given panorama depth <latex>D_k</latex>, the initial Gaussian center is</p>
<p><latex>\boldsymbol{\mu}_k = D_k \, \mathbf{d}(\theta_k, \phi_k)</latex></p>
<p>and the initial scale is latitude-aware, <latex>s_k \propto D_k \cos\phi_k</latex>, so the tangential footprint shrinks toward the poles. A lightweight residual head predicts corrections <latex>(\Delta\theta, \Delta\phi, \Delta z)</latex> in angular–inverse-depth space; this adapts SHARP’s depth-guided residual Gaussian prediction from planar pinhole images to spherical ERP geometry.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:moverse:pipeline]]</p>

<p>Stage III renders the scaffold along the requested trajectory and refines the conditioning stream into final video. A bidirectional diffusion teacher (initialized from Wan2.1-T2V-1.3B) is trained for high-quality Gaussian-conditioned rendering; it is then distilled into a causal autoregressive student with a bounded KV cache, so the online model only has to do local refinement while the explicit scaffold carries long-range spatial memory. The authors report 8 FPS on a single RTX 4090.</p>

<p>We cloned the official repository, but it is currently a placeholder: only a README, an icon, and a pipeline figure, with a note that release is pending corporate compliance review. So this thread is built on the paper plus two humble probes. The first probe (<code>probe_stagei_shift_equivariance.py</code>) shows that circular horizontal padding gives exact shift equivariance on a toy latent, while zero padding introduces a seam—validating the topology argument. The second probe (<code>probe_stageii_erp_to_gaussians.py</code>) reconstructs the spherical back-projection, latitude-aware scale initialization, and angular–inverse-depth residual composition on a synthetic box room.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:moverse:probe-gaussians]]</p>

<p>The probe’s numbers confirm the geometry is non-trivial: mean Gaussian scale at the equator is 0.196 versus 0.018 near the poles, so omitting the <latex>\cos\phi</latex> correction would badly overestimate polar footprints. The main open question is robustness: Stage I hallucinates the entire 360° world from one NFOV image, and there is no feedback path from Stages II/III to correct a bad panorama. The real-time claim is architecturally plausible because memory lives in the explicit scaffold, but independent verification is blocked until the causal student, TAEHV decoder, and checkpoints are released.</p>

<h1>Theme 2 — Action Interfaces for Visual Agents</h1>

<p>Once an agent can see and act, how should it express those actions? This theme treats the interface itself as a first-class design decision.</p>

