<h2>SpatialClaw: Rethinking Action Interface for Agentic Spatial Reasoning</h2>
<p>Cho et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.13673">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.13673">PDF</a> · <a href="https://spatialclaw.github.io/">Project</a></p>

<p>SpatialClaw studies a specific but underexplored design choice: the <b>action interface</b> of a tool-augmented spatial-reasoning agent. Existing agents either generate one complete Python program before seeing any intermediate result, or invoke a fixed menu of structured JSON tool calls. Both limit the agent’s ability to compose perception outputs in task-specific ways. SpatialClaw instead treats <b>code as the action interface</b>: at each step the VLM writes one executable Python cell in a persistent kernel pre-loaded with input frames, perception tools (SAM3, Depth-Anything-3), and scientific libraries (NumPy, SciPy, Matplotlib).</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:spatialclaw:interface]]</p>

<p>The kernel exposes six entry points: <code>InputImages</code>, <code>Metadata</code>, <code>tools</code>, <code>show(...)</code>, <code>vlm</code>, and <code>ReturnAnswer(...)</code>. Each cell can call tools, compose their outputs, register intermediate images via <code>show()</code>, and leave variables in the persistent namespace for later cells. An outer loop runs plan → code → AST safety check → execute → feedback (stdout, variables, images, errors) → reflect/continue. The system prompt encodes general spatial-reasoning discipline rather than task-specific templates, so the same configuration is used across all 20 benchmarks and six backbone models.</p>

<p>We cloned the official implementation (<code>NVlabs/SpatialClaw</code>) and traced the LangGraph workflow, the persistent Jupyter kernel manager, the AST sandbox, and the tool wrappers. The code matches the paper’s architectural description. We also cloned pySpatial to confirm it is single-pass: <code>generate_code_from_query()</code> → <code>execute_code()</code> → <code>answer()</code>, with no per-step revision. VADAR’s repository contains only project-page HTML, so we could not trace it.</p>

<p>The key empirical result is that the interface itself drives the gains. On Gemma4-31B, the action-interface ablation shows No-tool 53.4, Single-pass code 55.2, Structured tool-call 56.7, and SpatialClaw 59.9. Removing predefined utility wrappers loses only −0.5 pp, because the agent reimplements them with NumPy/SciPy; removing the perception tools entirely still beats the no-tool baseline by +2.7 pp. The largest gains concentrate in camera motion, multi-view/viewpoint reasoning, and relative direction—exactly the categories that demand chained geometric computation across frames or viewpoints.</p>

<p>To make the mechanism concrete without GPUs or a real VLM, we built a minimal reconstruction in <code>runs/2026-06-12-spatialclaw-moverse-labvla/spatialclaw-2606.13673/code/</code>: a mock persistent kernel, mock perception tools, an AST sandbox, and a scripted 4-step session that segments two objects, reconstructs metric 3D geometry, computes camera-to-object distances, and returns <code>ReturnAnswer("car")</code>. The probe runs end-to-end and produces a synthetic input image plus step-by-step feedback logs.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:spatialclaw:probe-input]]</p>

<p>The takeaway is that for spatial reasoning, the action space should be as expressive as Python evaluated in a persistent loop, not as restrictive as a fixed JSON tool menu. The remaining bottleneck is perception quality and VLM hallucination, not the interface itself.</p>

