<h1>Cross-Cutting Observation: Explicit Memory, Local Computation</h1>

<p>A single design pattern appears across the deep threads. MoVerse puts durable scene memory in an explicit 3D Gaussian scaffold and uses the video model only for local refinement. LabVLA builds a reusable synthetic corpus so the policy can learn laboratory protocols offline before online deployment. SpatialClaw keeps intermediate spatial evidence as persistent Python variables rather than one-shot tool outputs. In each case the authors are trading away the temptation to let a single monolithic model do everything, and instead factor the problem into <b>memory that persists</b> plus <b>computation that runs on demand</b>. The current pool suggests this factorization is becoming a default engineering move for embodied agents and world models, not just a theoretical preference.</p>

<h1>Methodology Note</h1>

<p>We pulled the 2026-06-11/12 Hugging Face Papers pool, filtered for relevance to robotics, multimodal agents, world models, and control, then selected three papers for deep investigation. Each thread includes code inspection, related-work comparison, and a small probe or reconstruction preserved under <code>runs/2026-06-12-spatialclaw-moverse-labvla/&lt;thread-id&gt;/</code>. Full empirical numbers were not independently reproduced where the released artifacts were incomplete (MoVerse, RoboGenesis) or the full evaluation required multi-GPU infrastructure (SpatialClaw); those limits are stated explicitly.</p>
